				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				Not to mention the fact that the software writers/developers basically &quot;own&quot; the world they created.  Did they not use their own time to create this world. (isn't that what's being debated, the value of gamers' time??)  If, in fact, the time-value argument is to be used, they (lawyers, whoever) cannot ignore the fact that the developers used their time to create this world, and therefore, in a sense, own it.  Regardless of a player's time to acquire a said item and/or player/account, that would not exist without the world itself.  So, ownership of the world obviously comes in first, for without the world, the player/account/item(s) in question, would not, in fact, COULD not exist.  Therefore, it is highly likely that the owners of the world have final say-so about the legal aspects of accounts used to access their &quot;world&quot;.  Namely, the developers DO have a right to say whether or not accounts/players/items could be sold (for &quot;real-world&quot; currency), primarily because it is THEIR world to begin with.<BR>
Also, note that if &quot;time-value&quot; is to be used as an argument, in any case, we would have to assign a finite value to the &quot;value&quot; of time itself.  Primarily, if Bill Gates decided to purchase an account that perhaps I also wanted, I think he would definitely win, for he obviously has more money.  Does that mean my time is ANY less valuable than his? (time it would take to get said player-level/item.)  Does it mean, that the person's time who sold the account is more valuable? (Because he, afterall, ends up with the money.)  I believe not.<BR>
I still think the game-world developers have a right to say what can/cannot happen in real life auctions, because it affects THEIR game world.  To say that because of the &quot;time-value&quot; argument of someone to acquire something is valid, is to immediately INVALIDATE any work the developers have done.<BR>
The items/accounts being sold would not even BE there without them.  They should have final say.<BR>
Thank you.<BR>
Gessler
